---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout title="Education Loan | TrueCred Loan Expert">

<!-- Page Hero -->
  <section class="page-hero">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="breadcrumb">
        <a href="/">Home</a>
        <span class="sep"><i class="fas fa-chevron-right"></i></span>
        <a href="#">Loans</a>
        <span class="sep"><i class="fas fa-chevron-right"></i></span>
        <span>Education Loan</span>
      </div>
      <h1>Education Loan</h1>
      <p class="hero-sub">Fund your dreams of studying at top universities in India and abroad. Get education loans with competitive rates, moratorium periods, and tax benefits to make quality education affordable.</p>
      <div class="hero-highlights">
        <div class="highlight-item">
          <i class="fas fa-globe"></i> Study in India/Abroad
        </div>
        <div class="highlight-item">
          <i class="fas fa-indian-rupee-sign"></i> Up to ₹1 Cr
        </div>
        <div class="highlight-item">
          <i class="fas fa-receipt"></i> Tax Benefits
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Page Content -->
  <section class="page-content">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="content-grid">

        <!-- Main Content -->
        <div class="content-main">
          <h2>Education Loan Overview</h2>
          <p>An Education Loan helps students finance their higher education at recognized institutions in India and abroad. The loan covers tuition fees, hostel charges, examination fees, book and equipment costs, travel expenses, and other education-related expenditures. Both undergraduate and postgraduate courses are covered, including professional programs like MBA, engineering, medicine, law, and more.</p>
          <p>Education loans come with a moratorium period (course duration plus 6-12 months) during which students are not required to pay EMIs. Interest repayment during the moratorium can significantly reduce the total interest burden. Additionally, the interest paid on education loans is eligible for tax deduction under Section 80E of the Income Tax Act for up to 8 years.</p>

          <div class="info-grid">
            <div class="info-box">
              <span class="info-value">8.5%</span>
              <span class="info-label">Interest Rate (p.a.)</span>
            </div>
            <div class="info-box">
              <span class="info-value">₹1 Cr</span>
              <span class="info-label">Maximum Loan Amount</span>
            </div>
            <div class="info-box">
              <span class="info-value">6-12 Mo</span>
              <span class="info-label">Moratorium Period</span>
            </div>
          </div>

          <h3>Education Loan Interest Rates 2026</h3>
          <table class="rate-table">
            <thead>
              <tr>
                <th>Bank / NBFC</th>
                <th>Interest Rate (p.a.)</th>
                <th>Max Loan Amount</th>
                <th>Max Tenure</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr>
                <td>SBI</td>
                <td>8.55% onwards</td>
                <td>₹1.5 Crore</td>
                <td>15 Years</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>HDFC Credila</td>
                <td>9.50% onwards</td>
                <td>₹1 Crore</td>
                <td>12 Years</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>Axis Bank</td>
                <td>9.25% onwards</td>
                <td>₹75 Lakh</td>
                <td>15 Years</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>ICICI Bank</td>
                <td>9.75% onwards</td>
                <td>₹1 Crore</td>
                <td>12 Years</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>Avanse Financial</td>
                <td>10.50% onwards</td>
                <td>₹75 Lakh</td>
                <td>10 Years</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>

          <h3>Education Loans: India vs Abroad</h3>
          <ul class="feature-list">
            <li><i class="fas fa-check-circle"></i> <strong>Domestic Education Loan:</strong> Available up to ₹15 Lakh without collateral for studies at recognized Indian institutions including IITs, IIMs, AIIMS, and other top colleges</li>
            <li><i class="fas fa-check-circle"></i> <strong>Abroad Education Loan:</strong> Higher loan amounts up to ₹1 Crore available with collateral for studies at universities in the USA, UK, Canada, Australia, Germany, and other countries</li>
            <li><i class="fas fa-check-circle"></i> <strong>Collateral-Free Loans:</strong> Loans up to ₹7.5 Lakh from public sector banks require no collateral or third-party guarantee as per government guidelines</li>
            <li><i class="fas fa-check-circle"></i> <strong>Government Subsidy:</strong> Students from economically weaker sections can avail interest subsidy under the Central Sector Interest Subsidy Scheme during the moratorium period</li>
            <li><i class="fas fa-check-circle"></i> <strong>Covered Expenses:</strong> Both domestic and abroad loans cover tuition fees, hostel, books, equipment, travel, and living expenses</li>
          </ul>

          <h3>Eligibility Criteria</h3>
          <ul class="feature-list">
            <li><i class="fas fa-check-circle"></i> Indian citizen with confirmed admission at a recognized institution in India or abroad</li>
            <li><i class="fas fa-check-circle"></i> Student age should be between 16 to 35 years at the time of application</li>
            <li><i class="fas fa-check-circle"></i> A co-applicant (parent, guardian, or spouse) is mandatory for all education loans</li>
            <li><i class="fas fa-check-circle"></i> Good academic record with minimum qualifying marks as per lender requirements</li>
            <li><i class="fas fa-check-circle"></i> Collateral required for loans above ₹7.5 Lakh (property, FD, or other securities accepted)</li>
          </ul>

          <h3>How to Apply for an Education Loan</h3>
          <div class="steps-grid">
            <div class="step-card">
              <div class="step-num">1</div>
              <h4>Get Admission</h4>
              <p>Secure admission at a recognized university or institution. Keep the offer letter and fee structure ready.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="step-card">
              <div class="step-num">2</div>
              <h4>Compare Lenders</h4>
              <p>Compare interest rates, processing fees, moratorium periods, and repayment terms across multiple banks.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="step-card">
              <div class="step-num">3</div>
              <h4>Submit Documents</h4>
              <p>Apply online or at a branch with all required academic, identity, and financial documents.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="step-card">
              <div class="step-num">4</div>
              <h4>Loan Disbursal</h4>
              <p>Upon approval, the loan is disbursed directly to the institution in stages as per the fee schedule.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <h3>Documents Required</h3>
          <ul class="feature-list">
            <li><i class="fas fa-file-alt"></i> Admission letter or offer letter from the institution</li>
            <li><i class="fas fa-file-alt"></i> Detailed fee structure and cost breakup from the institution</li>
            <li><i class="fas fa-file-alt"></i> Academic mark sheets (10th, 12th, graduation as applicable)</li>
            <li><i class="fas fa-file-alt"></i> Entrance exam score cards (GRE, GMAT, IELTS, TOEFL, CAT, etc.)</li>
            <li><i class="fas fa-file-alt"></i> Identity and address proof of student and co-applicant</li>
            <li><i class="fas fa-file-alt"></i> Income proof of co-applicant: salary slips or ITR for last 2 years</li>
            <li><i class="fas fa-file-alt"></i> Bank statements of co-applicant for last 6 months</li>
            <li><i class="fas fa-file-alt"></i> Collateral documents (if loan amount exceeds ₹7.5 Lakh)</li>
            <li><i class="fas fa-file-alt"></i> Passport and visa (for abroad education loans)</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <!-- Sidebar -->
        <div class="content-sidebar">
          <div class="sidebar-card">
            <h3>Apply for Education Loan</h3>
            <form class="sidebar-form" onsubmit="return false;">
              <div class="form-group">
                <input type="text" class="form-input" placeholder="Student Name" required>
              </div>
              <div class="form-group">
                <input type="tel" class="form-input" placeholder="Mobile Number" maxlength="10" required>
              </div>
              <div class="form-group">
                <select class="form-input" required>
                  <option value="" disabled selected>Course Type</option>
                  <option value="ug-india">UG in India</option>
                  <option value="pg-india">PG in India</option>
                  <option value="ug-abroad">UG Abroad</option>
                  <option value="pg-abroad">PG Abroad</option>
                  <option value="diploma">Diploma / Certificate</option>
                  <option value="phd">PhD / Research</option>
                </select>
              </div>
              <div class="form-group">
                <input type="text" class="form-input" placeholder="Loan Amount Required (₹)" required>
              </div>
              <button type="submit" class="btn btn-primary btn-block">Apply Now <i class="fas fa-arrow-right"></i></button>
            </form>
          </div>

          <div class="sidebar-card">
            <h3>Quick Links</h3>
            <div class="sidebar-links">
              <a href="/pages/personal-loan"><i class="fas fa-chevron-right"></i> Personal Loan</a>
              <a href="/pages/business-loan"><i class="fas fa-chevron-right"></i> Business Loan</a>
              <a href="/pages/home-loan"><i class="fas fa-chevron-right"></i> Home Loan</a>
              <a href="/pages/loan-against-property"><i class="fas fa-chevron-right"></i> Loan Against Property</a>
              <a href="/pages/gold-loan"><i class="fas fa-chevron-right"></i> Gold Loan</a>
              <a href="/pages/car-loan"><i class="fas fa-chevron-right"></i> Car Loan</a>
              <a href="/pages/credit-cards"><i class="fas fa-chevron-right"></i> Credit Cards</a>
              <a href="/pages/calculators"><i class="fas fa-chevron-right"></i> EMI Calculator</a>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

      </div>

      <!-- Page CTA -->
      <div class="page-cta">
        <div>
          <h3>Invest in Your Future with the Right Education Loan</h3>
          <p>Compare offers from top banks and NBFCs to find the best education loan for your dream course.</p>
        </div>
        <a href="#" class="btn btn-outline btn-lg">Talk to Expert <i class="fas fa-arrow-right"></i></a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- FAQ Section -->
  <section class="faq-section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header">
        <span class="section-tag">FAQs</span>
        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
        <p>Everything you need to know about Education Loans</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-list">
        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question">Can I get an education loan without collateral? <i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></button>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <div class="faq-answer-inner">Yes, most public sector banks offer collateral-free education loans up to ₹7.5 Lakh as per the Indian Banks' Association (IBA) guidelines. For loans between ₹7.5 Lakh and ₹20 Lakh, some NBFCs like HDFC Credila and Avanse also offer collateral-free options based on the co-applicant's income and the student's admission profile. For higher amounts, especially for abroad education, collateral is typically required.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question">What is the moratorium period in an education loan? <i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></button>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <div class="faq-answer-inner">The moratorium period is the time during which you are not required to pay EMIs on your education loan. It typically includes the entire duration of the course plus an additional 6 to 12 months after completion (or 6 months after getting a job, whichever is earlier). During this period, interest continues to accrue on the loan. Paying simple interest during the moratorium can significantly reduce your total repayment amount.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question">What tax benefits are available on education loans? <i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></button>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <div class="faq-answer-inner">Under Section 80E of the Income Tax Act, the interest paid on education loans is fully deductible from your taxable income. There is no upper limit on the deduction amount. This benefit is available for a maximum of 8 years from the year you start repaying the loan or until the interest is fully repaid, whichever comes first. The deduction can be claimed by the student or the parent, whoever is repaying the loan.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question">Which courses are covered under education loans? <i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></button>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <div class="faq-answer-inner">Education loans cover a wide range of courses at recognized institutions including undergraduate and postgraduate degrees (B.Tech, M.Tech, MBBS, MBA, M.Sc, etc.), professional certifications (CA, CFA, CPA), diploma and vocational programs, PhD and research programs, and courses at recognized foreign universities. The institution must be approved by UGC, AICTE, or equivalent regulatory bodies for domestic loans, and by the respective country's accreditation body for abroad loans.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question">How is the education loan disbursed? <i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></button>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <div class="faq-answer-inner">Education loans are typically disbursed in stages aligned with the institution's fee payment schedule. The tuition fee component is paid directly to the institution's bank account, while the living expenses and equipment allowance may be credited to the student's or co-applicant's account. For abroad education, the bank directly converts the amount to foreign currency and transfers it as per the university's requirements. The loan sanction letter specifies the disbursement schedule.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Footer -->

</BaseLayout>
